



VMSTAT COMMAND:
(1) What is the vmstat command? (History, invention, authors)
vmstat means Virtual Memory Statistics.
It is a built-in Unix/Linux command used to check the overall performance of a system.
Short History
First introduced in BSD Unix in the late 1970s‚Äì1980s.
Later included in System V Unix.
Today, the Linux version comes from the procps/procps-ng project, maintained by Linux open-source developers.
Purpose
It gives information about:
Memory usage
CPU activity
Processes
Swap memory
Disk I/O
In simple words:
üëâ vmstat shows how healthy your system is.

(2) Why is vmstat useful for System Administrators?
System administrators use vmstat because it helps them:
‚úî Monitor memory
Find if RAM is free, used, cached, or swapped.
‚úî Detect CPU load
Check if CPU is idle or overloaded.
‚úî Detect system performance problems
Helpful when the system is slow or hanging.
‚úî Identify I/O bottlenecks
Find if the disk is reading/writing too much.
‚úî Troubleshoot in real time
Using vmstat <seconds> to watch live changes.
In short:
üëâ vmstat helps admins understand what is happening inside the system at that moment.

(3) How does the vmstat command work? (With example)
Basic command
vmstat
This shows a single report of system performance.
Example Output
procs -----------memory---------- ---swap-- -----io---- -system-- ------cpu-----
 r  b   swpd   free   buff  cache   si   so    bi    bo   in   cs us sy id wa st
 1  0      0  82000  12000 250000    0    0     5    10  200  300  5  3 90  2  0
Meaning (simple)
r ‚Äì number of processes waiting for CPU
free ‚Äì free RAM
cache ‚Äì cached memory
us, sy, id ‚Äì CPU usage (user, system, idle)
So, vmstat quickly shows the overall status of your system.

(4) Snapshots (simple illustrated examples)
Snapshot 1: Running vmstat
$ vmstat
procs -----------memory---------- ---swap-- -----io---- -system-- ------cpu-----
 r  b   swpd   free   buff  cache   si   so    bi    bo   in   cs us sy id wa st
 0  0      0 102500  20000 300400    0    0     3     5  180  250  4  2 92  2  0
Snapshot 2: Continuous monitoring
$ vmstat 2
procs ---------memory----------- ---swap-- -----io---- -system-- ------cpu-----
 r  b   swpd   free   buff  cache   si   so    bi    bo   in   cs us sy id wa st
 1  0      0  98000  21000 310000    0    0     5     9  150  210 10  5 82  3  0
 2  1      0  96000  21000 315000    0    0     8     4  170  230 12  4 80  4  0

(5) Options & Flags (5‚Äì6 important ones)
1. vmstat -s ‚Äî Show detailed memory statistics
vmstat -s
Displays readable, summary numbers.
2. vmstat -a ‚Äî Show active & inactive memory
vmstat -a
3. vmstat -d ‚Äî Show disk statistics
vmstat -d
4. vmstat -D ‚Äî Summary disk statistics
vmstat -D
5. vmstat -p /dev/sda1 ‚Äî Show stats for a partition
vmstat -p /dev/sda1
6. vmstat -t ‚Äî Timestamp in output
vmstat -t 2

Sources for detailed flags and options
You can check full details here:
Linux manual page:
man vmstat
Online references:
https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/vmstat.8.html
https://linux.die.net/man/8/vmstat

VMSTAT 2 COMMAND:

(1) What is the command? (History, invention, authors)
vmstat 2 is a Linux/Unix command that runs vmstat but refreshes the system statistics every 2 seconds.
Short History
vmstat was introduced in early UNIX systems in the late 1970s.
It became part of BSD UNIX and later System V UNIX.
The Linux version used today comes from the procps-ng package.
It has been built and improved by many UNIX engineers and open-source developers over many years.
In simple words:
vmstat 2 is the live-monitoring version of vmstat, showing system health every 2 seconds.

(2) Why is vmstat 2 useful for System Administrators?
System admins use vmstat 2 mainly because it shows real-time updates.
It is useful for:
‚úî Watching CPU usage change live
‚úî Monitoring memory usage over time
‚úî Detecting sudden spikes in processes
‚úî Observing disk I/O activity happening every few seconds
‚úî Checking if the system slows down randomly
‚úî Live performance troubleshooting
In simple words:
vmstat 2 works like a ‚Äúlive heartbeat monitor‚Äù for the system.

(3) How does vmstat 2 work? (With example)
The basic command is:
vmstat 2
2 means refresh the info every 2 seconds
It keeps running until you press CTRL + C
Example Output
$ vmstat 2
procs -----------memory---------- ---swap-- -----io---- -system-- ------cpu-----
 r  b   swpd   free   buff   cache   si   so    bi    bo   in   cs us sy id wa st
 1  0      0  95000  12000 270000    0    0    12    14  150  200 10  3 85  2  0
 2  1      0  90000  12000 275000    0    0     8     5  165  215 14  5 78  3  0
 1  0      0  92000  12000 280000    0    0     5     8  140  190  9  2 88  1  0
What‚Äôs happening here?
Every 2 seconds, you see new values.
If CPU or memory usage changes, you can see it immediately.
This is why the command is great for live monitoring.

(4) Snapshots of vmstat 2 (Illustrations)
üì∏ Snapshot 1 ‚Äî When you run the command
$ vmstat 2
procs -----------memory---------- ---swap-- -----io---- -system-- ------cpu-----
 r  b   swpd   free   buff   cache   si   so    bi    bo   in   cs us sy id wa st

üì∏ Snapshot 2 ‚Äî After 2 seconds
 1  0      0  98000  15000 300000    0    0     7     5  120  180 11  4 82  3  0

üì∏ Snapshot 3 ‚Äî After another 2 seconds
 2  1      0  94000  15000 310000    0    0    10     8  150  230 15  6 75  4  0
These snapshots show how the numbers change over time.

(5) Options & Flags for vmstat (6 important ones)
Even though vmstat 2 uses a refresh interval, it can still use many flags.

1. vmstat -s 2 ‚Üí Show detailed stats every 2 seconds
vmstat -s 2

2. vmstat -a 2 ‚Üí Show active/inactive memory every 2 seconds
vmstat -a 2

3. vmstat -d 2 ‚Üí Disk stats every 2 seconds
vmstat -d 2

4. vmstat -p /dev/sda1 2 ‚Üí Partition stats every 2 seconds
vmstat -p /dev/sda1 2

5. vmstat -t 2 ‚Üí Add timestamp to every update
vmstat -t 2
Shows time of each refresh.

6. vmstat -m 2 ‚Üí Show kernel slab memory every 2 seconds
vmstat -m 2

Sources for full flag list
You can refer to:
üìå Linux manual
man vmstat
üìå Online documentation
https://linux.die.net/man/8/vmstat
https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/vmstat.8.html
